        "qa": "Q. What if I give too much of Azith 100mg Tablet by mistake?::: Azith 100mg Tablet is unlikely to cause any harm if an extra dose is given by mistake. However, if you think you have given too much of Azith 100mg Tablet to your child, immediately speak to a doctor. Overdose may cause unwanted side effects and may even worsen your child’s condition.| Q. Are there any possible serious side effects of Azith 100mg Tablet?::: Some serious side effects of this medicine include persistent vomiting, kidney damage, allergy, diarrhea, and severe gastrointestinal infections. Always consult your child’s doctor for help in such a situation.| Q. Can other medicines be given at the same time as Azith 100mg Tablet?::: Azith 100mg Tablet can sometimes interact with other medicines or substances. Tell your doctor about any other medicines your child is taking before starting Azith 100mg Tablet. Also, check with your child’s doctor before giving any medicine to your child.| Q. Can I get my child vaccinated while on treatment with Azith 100mg Tablet?::: Antibiotics usually do not interfere with the ingredients in vaccines or cause a bad reaction in a child who has just been vaccinated. However, children taking antibiotics should not get vaccinated until they recover from the illness. As soon as your child feels better, the vaccine can be given.| Q. Which all lab tests should my child undergo while taking Azith 100mg Tablet on a long-term basis?::: The doctor may prescribe getting kidney function tests and liver function tests periodically to keep a check on your child’s condition.| Q. Can Azith 100mg Tablet impact my child’s digestion?::: Children often have a sensitive stomach and develop a stomach upset while taking medicines. When antibiotics are given, the good bacteria in their gastrointestinal tract may too get affected. Azith 100mg Tablet may kill off good bacteria along with the bad ones, increasing your child’s risk of developing other infections. So, in case your child is having diarrhea while on Azith 100mg Tablet, do not stop the medicine course. Instead, call your child’s doctor to ask the next steps. In some cases, the doctor may alter the dose.| Q. Why is Azith 100mg Tablet given for 3 days?::: The duration of treatment depends on the type of infection being treated and the age of the patient. Azith 100mg Tablet is not necessarily given for 3 days. In most bacterial infections, a single dose of 500 mg is given for 3 days. Alternatively, it can be given as 500 mg once on day 1 and then 250 mg once from day 2 to day 5. In some cases of infection such as genital ulcer disease, it is given as a single 1 gram dose. Therefore, you must stick to the regimen advised by your doctor.| Q. What should I avoid while taking Azith 100mg Tablet?::: Generally, it is recommended that patients taking Azith 100mg Tablet should avoid taking any antacid with this medicine as this can affect the overall effectiveness of Azith 100mg Tablet. It is also recommended to avoid exposure to sunlight or tanning beds as Azith 100mg Tablet increases the risk of sunburn.| Q. Is Azith 100mg Tablet a strong antibiotic?::: Azith 100mg Tablet is an effective antibiotic that is used for the treatment of many bacterial infections. Compared to other antibiotics, Azith 100mg Tablet has a longer half-life which means that it stays in the body for a long time because of which it is given once a day and for a short span of time. Other antibiotics comparatively have a shorter half-life and are usually given twice, thrice, or four times a day.| Q. Can you get a yeast infection from taking Azith 100mg Tablet?::: Some people may get a fungal or yeast infection known as thrush after taking Azith 100mg Tablet. Antibiotics such as Azith 100mg Tablet can kill the normal or ‘good bacteria’ of your intestine responsible for preventing thrush. You should inform your doctor if you get a sore or vaginal itching or discharge. Also, inform your doctor if you get a white patch in the mouth or tongue after taking Azith 100mg Tablet or soon after stopping it.",
        "how_it_works": "Azith 100mg Tablet is an antibiotic. It works by interfering with the synthesis of essential proteins required by bacteria to perform important functions. By doing so, it stops the infection-causing bacteria from growing further and prevents the infection from spreading.",
        "interaction": "Azith 100mg Tablet & Alestol 10mg Tablet :  Levels of Astemizole are increased by Azithromycin which increases the risk of QT prolongation (heart rhythm disorder) and life-threatening irregular heartbeat. | Azith 100mg Tablet & Astelong 10mg Tablet :  Levels of Astemizole are increased by Azithromycin which increases the risk of QT prolongation (heart rhythm disorder) and life-threatening irregular heartbeat. | Azith 100mg Tablet & Astem 10mg Tablet :  Levels of Astemizole are increased by Azithromycin which increases the risk of QT prolongation (heart rhythm disorder) and life-threatening irregular heartbeat. | Azith 100mg Tablet & Astelong 5mg Oral Suspension :  Levels of Astemizole are increased by Azithromycin which increases the risk of QT prolongation (heart rhythm disorder) and life-threatening irregular heartbeat. | Azith 100mg Tablet & Acemiz Plus 5mg Suspension :  Levels of Astemizole are increased by Azithromycin which increases the risk of QT prolongation (heart rhythm disorder) and life-threatening irregular heartbeat. | Azith 100mg Tablet & Acipax 10mg Tablet :  Levels of Astemizole are increased by Azithromycin which increases the risk of QT prolongation (heart rhythm disorder) and life-threatening irregular heartbeat. | Azith 100mg Tablet & Regubeat 100mg Tablet :  Concurrent use of Disopyramide and Azithromycin should be avoided. Azithromycin increases Disopyramide levels, and this has resulted in an abnormal heart beat and heart block. | Azith 100mg Tablet & Norpace New Capsule :  Concurrent use of Disopyramide and Azithromycin should be avoided. Azithromycin increases Disopyramide levels, and this has resulted in an abnormal heart beat and heart block. | Azith 100mg Tablet & Norpace 100 Capsule :  Concurrent use of Disopyramide and Azithromycin should be avoided. Azithromycin increases Disopyramide levels, and this has resulted in an abnormal heart beat and heart block. | Azith 100mg Tablet & Ebast 5mg Tablet DT :  Levels of Ebastine are increased by Azithromycin but there are no significant interactions. Use of Ebastine and Azithromycin should be avoided at the same time, though.",
